# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: turner-memorial-hospital
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Plans for the complex were announced in 2010.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The facility, which cost £15 million to construct, opened in December 2013.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] It was the first healthcare facility to be completed in Scotland under the hub framework of the Scottish Futures Trust.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village, which is designed to offer services to 700 patients a day, contains 275 rooms including three dental suites, two minor procedure rooms and 29 consulting rooms.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Services being run from the health village include: cardiac rehabilitation, dentistry, dietetics, physiotherapy, podiatry, radiology, sexual health, speech and language therapy and minor surgery.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] An endoscopy service was provided from June 2014.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village acts as an educational resource for patients, carers and community-based staff.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village also provides improved access to community based learning opportunities for healthcare professionals such as general practitioners (GPs) and GP trainees.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Work on a mural on the side of the building began in July 2021.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] It is being painted by Fanakapan, a London-based artist, as part of the 2021 NuArt Festival.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital has its origins in the a small facility established at Guestrow in 1870.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] It moved to Barrett's Close in 1893 and to Castle Street in 1900.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The move to a new building, which was designed by James Brown Nicol and built between 1934 and 1937, formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by Professor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] An ante-natal hospital was added in 1941 and the facility joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital progressed to stage two accreditation of the Baby Friendly Hospital Initiative in July 2011.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Construction of new hospital buildings - for The Baird Family Hospital and Anchor cancer centre - was delayed after costs escalated from £163m to £223m.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] In February 2020, forecast completion dates were 2022 and March 2023 respectively.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The Department of Obstetrics and Gynaecology, University of Aberdeen, is based at the hospital, which conducts a variety of research with an emphasis on obstetric epidemiology (including maternal mortality and morbidity), infertility and the prevention of cancer in women.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Aberdeen is also particularly known for its research into multiple pregnancy.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The associated **Dugald Baird Centre for Research on Women's Health** was set up in 1995 and is primarily a research unit, with consultative and teaching responsibilities.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Current work focuses on a number of themes in reproductive health research and methodological development in evaluation.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The centre is named after Sir Dugald Baird (1899–1986), Regius Professor of Midwifery at the University of Aberdeen from 1937 to 1965.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The **Aberdeen Royal Infirmary** (**ARI**) is the largest hospital in the Grampian area, located on the Foresterhill site in Aberdeen, Scotland.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI is a teaching hospital offering tertiary care for a population of over 600,000 across the north-east of Scotland.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] It offers all medical specialities with the exception of heart and liver transplants.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Aberdeen Royal Infirmary has it origins in a facility established at Woolmanhill in 1739.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The move to the current site formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by the Scottish doctor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The granite buildings on the site were designed by James Brown Nicol.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital was officially opened by the Duke and Duchess of York on 23 September 1936—King Edward VIII had been due to open the infirmary but he called off his visit and instead went to Ballater railway station to meet the American socialite Wallis Simpson off her train.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The first patients were admitted a month later.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In the 1980s the English physicist John Mallard led a team which built the first whole body magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scanner.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The world's first whole-body MRI scanner was used for diagnostic imaging between 1980 and 1983.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The prototype machine, Mark One, was put on display in the hospital's art gallery in February 2016.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Following fundraising by *Evening Express* readers, in 1992 a Siemens scanner costing £870,000 was brought.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1984, a hyperbaric oxygen unit was built for the treatment of decompression illness and the hospital's in vitro fertilisation unit achieved a number of successful pregnancies in 1985, its first year of operation.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1986, a new £550,000 out-patient eye clinic opened, offering corrective laser eye surgery, and in 1989, the hospital introduced a breast cancer screening service for women over the age of 50, with X-rays taken every three years.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2013, a £110m emergency care centre development was completed.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] This was the first time that the Foresterhill campus had hosted emergency and urgent care facilities in the same building, and 75% of the beds in the centre are single-occupancy.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In February 2014, it was revealed that the hospital has a repairs backlog of £60 million.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] On 26 June 2014, John Swinney, the then Finance Secretary, announced a £120 million investment for a new cancer centre and maternity hospital on the site.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2016, the ARI became one of four major trauma centres as part of a national major trauma network in Scotland.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Social workers can be contacted in the hospital, and a branch of the Citizens Advice Bureau is based there.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by the volunteer-run radio station, Grampian Hospital Radio.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by several bus services with regular connections to Aberdeen city centre and service to places as far as Inverurie and Oldmeldrum in the north, Inverness in the West and Cove Bay in the south.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new multistorey carpark with space for over 1,000 cars was opened in 2017.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] There are close links with the University of Aberdeen's medical school and there has been pioneering research in many fields, including the development of MRI and positron emission tomography (PET) scanning.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new PET scanner was installed in 2006.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI has been one of the centres evaluating telemedicine equipment and developing services in Scotland.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Academy of Medical Royal Colleges and Faculties in Scotland produced a report entitled "Learning from serious failings in care" in July 2015.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The investigation was launched after scandals in the health service in 2013 and 2014 leading to concerns about patient safety and care at the infirmary.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] They found leadership and accountability were often lacking and bullying was endemic.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The 20 recommendations for improvements in the NHS included a set of minimum safe staffing levels for consultants, doctors, nurses and other staff in hospital settings.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aboyne-hospital] The facility, which was designed by Jenkins & Marr, opened as an infectious diseases hospital in 1898.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aboyne-hospital] A ward pavilion was added in 1926 and, after the hospital had joined the National Health Service in 1948, a new health centre was added in 1980.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/aboyne-hospital] A major refurbishment started in 2002 and the newly modernised facilities were opened by Anne, Princess Royal in August 2003.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Chalmers Hospital was founded by Alexander Chalmers (died 11 August 1835), a merchant of Banff, who left the whole of his estate to be applied, upon the death of his wife, towards funding and building a hospital for the people in the Royal Burgh of Banff.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Mrs Chalmers died in 1861, and Chalmers Hospital opened on 19 July 1864.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The original 'deed of mortification' set out that this was for any destitute sick persons born, domiciled or resident in the Banff area, although in 1929 the trustees successfully petitioned for the removal of this restriction.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Some major redevelopment work began in October 2008, after the hospital attracted criticism for not being up to date, with some of the interior features having been there since the Second World War.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The hospital remained open during the work, although the Findlater ward services were moved to Campbell Hospital in Portsoy until the Findlater ward was refurbished, and Seafield and Deveron ward were merged.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The midwifery unit was demolished and rebuilt to provide modern facilities.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Numerous other internal changes were also made inside, including X-ray facilities being moved to a different area of the building.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The redevelopment also provided upgraded facilities for physiotherapy, occupational therapy, speech and language therapy and podiatry.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The completion of the redevelopment was recognised with a visit by the Princess Royal in March 2012.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The hospital is supported by GPs from Banff, Gamrie, Deveron, Macduff, Portsoy and Aberchirder Medical Practices.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/city-hospital-aberdeen] The facility, which was designed by William Smith, was established as an infectious diseases hospital in 1874.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/city-hospital-aberdeen] It was significantly expanded in 1895 and a new nurses' home was completed in 1931.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/city-hospital-aberdeen] During the 1964 Aberdeen typhoid outbreak, over 400 cases were diagnosed and the patients were quarantined at the City Hospital and Woodend Hospital, although no fatalities resulted.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] A **community hospital** can be purely a nominal designation or have a more specific meaning.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] When specific, it refers to a hospital that is accessible to the general public and provides a general or specific medical care which is usually short-term, in a cost-effective setting, and also focuses on preventing illnesses as opposed to only treating them.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] The word *community* often occurs in the name of the hospital.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] The word *community* is used in the sense of a *location-based community* for a community hospital.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] The following sections describe community hospitals when referred to in specific countries.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] In Singapore, community hospitals are a class of hospitals that provide continuation of care after discharge from acute hospitals, including rehabilitation and therapy.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] In Thailand, *community hospital* is a specific classification of public hospitals with a capacity of 150 beds or fewer.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] They serve local populations in provincial districts, providing primary care.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] An older term "cottage hospital" is now no longer applicable, having fallen from use because it inadequately describes the wide range of services being offered by their more modern equivalents.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] For many years the development of community hospitals was ad hoc, reflecting history rather than any rational planning.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] The Scottish model is usually the characteristic one and the one used in the rest of the United Kingdom, with some variations.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] Scottish "Community Hospital" is not a statutory phrase but it is often used where there is "a unit or centre providing an appropriate range and format of accessible health care facilities and resources".
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] Medical care is normally led by GPs, in liaison with consultant, nursing and allied health professional colleagues as necessary.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] Community hospitals can assist multidisciplinary working and can be used as an extended primary care resource.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] Community hospitals provide over 2,900 inpatient beds and over 750,000 outpatient, allied health professional and nurse led appointments.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] In many rural and remote communities this allows access to more specialised services and inpatient facilities closer to home.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] The (non-statutory) phrase is used in England in a similar manner to Scotland.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] Actual arrangements will be under legislation applicable to the English NHS.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] In Northern Ireland the phrase has similar use to Scotland but official publications give the appearance of *community hospitals* being more recent as a concept rather than a mere description.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] The (non-statutory) phrase is used in Wales in a similar (but possibly less restricted) manner to Scotland.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] Some are named as community hospitals and many more are also listed as having this function.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] Some community hospitals have been chosen to act as a hub for services.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] Actual arrangements will be under legislation applicable to NHS Wales/Gig Cymru.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] The American Hospital Association (AHA) defines community hospitals as "all nonfederal, short-term general, and other special hospitals." Health associations and hospital rating organizations, however, typically also say that teaching hospitals are not community hospitals.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] Some further restrict the community hospital definition to only include independently run facilities serving a local demographic.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] A basic definition, therefore, is a hospital serving a local community, run by local leaders, providing financial opportunities for the local economy.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] A community hospital can be either rural or urban.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] Many of the rural hospitals in Africa are small, community hospitals.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] Algeria has 273 community hospitals denoted **EPSP**, which stands for *etablissement de sante de publique de proximite* in French.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] Polyclinics are also used at the community level.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/community-hospital] There is an average of one polyclinic per 25,000 inhabitants in Algeria.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/turner-memorial-hospital] The hospital was financed by public subscription on the initiative of a Mr William Longmore.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/turner-memorial-hospital] It was officially opened as the "Turner Memorial Hospital" in memory of Dr Robert Turner in 1880.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/turner-memorial-hospital] It was expanded with the addition of two new wards in 1893 and further extended in 1926 and 1992.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/turner-memorial-hospital] The hospital has 22 beds providing for acute care, palliative care, rehabilitation and assessment and also a 24-hour minor injury unit.
[src:turner-memorial-hospital/turner-memorial-hospital] The hospital had links with Keith Community Radio which first broadcast in 1986.
